# Myki Multi-User Credentials (Secure Storage)
# Copy this file to .env and replace with your actual credentials
#
# IMPORTANT: The .env file is in .gitignore and will NOT be committed to version control
# Keep your actual credentials in .env (not tracked by git)

# ============================================================================
# User Credentials (Username, Card Number, Password)
# ============================================================================
# For each user in config/myki_config.json, set THREE environment variables:
# 1. MYKI_USERNAME_{KEY}     = Your actual Myki account username
# 2. MYKI_CARDNUMBER_{KEY}   = Your Myki card number
# 3. MYKI_PASSWORD_{KEY}     = Your Myki account password
#
# {KEY} = Config key from myki_config.json in UPPERCASE
#
# SECURITY: Config key can be different from your actual Myki username
# Example: Config key "koustubh" can map to actual username "koustubh25"

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Example 1: Config key "koustubh" maps to these environment variables:
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
MYKI_USERNAME_KOUSTUBH=koustubh25
MYKI_CARDNUMBER_KOUSTUBH=308425279093478
MYKI_PASSWORD_KOUSTUBH=your_password_here

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Example 2: Config key "john" maps to these environment variables:
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
MYKI_USERNAME_JOHN=john.doe@example.com
MYKI_CARDNUMBER_JOHN=123456789012345
MYKI_PASSWORD_JOHN=your_password_here

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Example 3: Config key "jane_smith" maps to these environment variables:
# Note: Underscores and dots in config key become underscores in env var name
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
MYKI_USERNAME_JANE_SMITH=janesmith42
MYKI_CARDNUMBER_JANE_SMITH=987654321098765
MYKI_PASSWORD_JANE_SMITH=your_password_here

# Add more users as needed following the same pattern


# ============================================================================
# Docker-Specific Configuration (Optional)
# ============================================================================
# These variables are used by Docker scripts (docker-run.sh, docker-debug.sh)
# They have sensible defaults but can be overridden if needed

# Display for Xvfb virtual display (default: :99)
# Only change if you have conflicts with other X servers
# DISPLAY=:99

# Chrome profile directory inside container (default: /app/browser_profile)
# Only change if you need a custom profile location
# CHROME_PROFILE_DIR=/app/browser_profile

# Python unbuffered output for real-time logging (default: 1)
# PYTHONUNBUFFERED=1


# ============================================================================
# Notes
# ============================================================================
# 1. Password Security:
#    - NEVER commit .env file to version control
#    - Keep .env file permissions restricted: chmod 600 .env
#    - Use strong, unique passwords for each Myki account
#
# 2. Username Mapping:
#    - Username in .env MUST match username in config/myki_config.json
#    - Use UPPERCASE for environment variable names
#    - Replace dots and dashes with underscores (e.g., jane.doe -> JANE_DOE)
#
# 3. Docker Usage:
#    - docker-run.sh automatically loads variables from .env file
#    - docker-debug.sh also loads .env for troubleshooting
#    - If .env is missing, scripts will warn but attempt to run
#
# 4. Local Testing:
#    - For local (non-Docker) testing, ensure .env is in project root
#    - python-dotenv library automatically loads .env file
#    - Verify with: python3 -c "import os; print(os.getenv('MYKI_PASSWORD_KOUSTUBH25'))"
